{"cursor":"4730","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"__notoc__ period.]]\n\n'Kuru' () was the name of a tribe in Iron Age India, which evolved into a\nMahajanapada state in the later Vedic period. The Kuru clan was based\nin the area of modern Haryana, Delhi and western parts of Uttar Pradesh (the\nregion of Doab, till Prayag/Kaushambi) in northern India. [http://books.goo-\ngle.co.in/books?id=VsujRFvaHI8C&pg=PA63&dq=Kuru+Kaushambi&hl=en&ei=I4hXT5PeM5Gs-\nrAf-xJD-Cw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=book-\nthumbnail&resnum=1&ved=0CDMQ6wEwAA#v=onepage&q=Kuru%20Kaushambi&f=false The\nHistory of India], edited by Kenneth Pletcher; Chapter: The Development of\nIndian Civilization from C. 1500 BCE To 300 CE|63\n\nThe Kurus figure prominently in the Rigveda. The Kurus here appear as a branch\nof the early Indo-Aryans, ruling the Ganga-Jamuna Doab and modern Haryana\n(earlier Eastern Punjab). The focus in the later Vedic period shifted out of\nPunjab, into the Doab, and thus to the Kuru clan. [http://books.google.co.i-\nn/books?id=0obUy_W9NREC&pg=PA63&dq=prayag+Rig+veda&hl=en&ei=PIFXT5n7N8HTrQfo2sS-\nODA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=book-\nthumbnail&resnum=4&ved=0CEEQ6wEwAw#v=onepage&q=prayag%20Rig%20veda&f=false The\nGanges In Myth And History] The increasing number and size of Painted Grey\nWare (PGW) settlements in the Doab area shows this. These developments resulted\nin the substantial enlargement of certain settlements such as Hastinapur and\nKaushambi towards the end of the Later Vedic period. These settlements slowly\nbegan to acquire characteristics of towns.\n\nThe Kuru tribe was formed, in the Early Vedic period, as a result of the\nalliance and merger between the Bharata and Puru tribes. National Council of\nEducational Research and Training, History Text Book, Part 1, India They\nformed the first political center of the Vedic period, with its capital\ninitially at Hastinapur, and were the center of political power during roughly\n1200 to 800 BCE. M Witzel, Early Sanskritization: Origin and Development of\nthe Kuru state, EJVS vol. 1 no. 4 (1995); also in B. KÃ¶lver (ed.), Recht, Staat\nund Verwaltung im klassischen Indien. The state, the Law, and Administration in\nClassical India, MÃ¼nchen, R. Oldenbourg, 1997, p.27-52 Towards the end of\nthe Early Vedic period, the capital of the Kurus was transferred to Kaushambi,\nin the lower Doab, after Hastinapur was destroyed by floods [http://books.-\ngoogle.co.in/books?id=VsujRFvaHI8C&pg=PA63&dq=Kuru+Kaushambi&hl=en&ei=I4hXT5PeM-\n5GsrAf-xJD-Cw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=book-\nthumbnail&resnum=1&ved=0CDMQ6wEwAA#v=onepage&q=Kuru%20Kaushambi&f=false The\nHistory of India], edited by Kenneth Pletcher; Chapter: The Development of\nIndian Civilization from C.1500 BCE To 300 CE|63 as well as because of\nupheavals in the Kuru family itself. [http://kaushambhi.nic.in/ Kaushambhi.nic.in] [http://www.all-\nart.org/Visual_History/01india1.htm All-art.org]\n\nIn the late Vedic period (by the 6th century BC), the Kuru dynasty evolved into\nKuru and Vats kingdoms, ruling over Upper Doab/Delhil/Haryana and lower Doab,\nrespectively. The Vatsa branch of the Kuru dynasty further divided into Vats\n(Kaushambi) and Vats(Mathura) branches. [http://upgov.nic.in/uphistory.aspx\nPolitical History of Uttar Pradesh]; Govt of Uttar Pradesh, official\nwebsite. The Atharvaveda (XX.127) refers to certain Parikshita as the\n\"Chief of the Kurus\". Raychaudhuri, H. C. (1972). Political History of\nAncient India: From the Accession of Parikshit to the Extinction of the Gupta\nDynasty, Calcutta:University of Calcutta, pp.11\n","linknr":262,"url":"Kuru_(Hindu_mythology)","recorded":1374766650,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Kuru_Kingdom&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Kuru_Kingdom&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Kuru_Kingdom